Patch Set 5:

@Jorge I checked the drools CSITs and they seem to be working fine with this change. Is there any other place I should check where drools is using the AAI simulator?

Patch Set 5:

> Patch Set 5:
> 
> @Jorge I checked the drools CSITs and they seem to be working fine with this change. Is there any other place I should check where drools is using the AAI simulator?

The aai simulator is used in the feature-controlloop-utils in drools-applications.   The s3p.jmx for jmeter in drools-applications is used for vfirewall, vcpe, .. and in the ONSETs carry the AAI info for the queries, it is typically used with the feature-controlloop-utils  The drools-applications junits for the usecases controller also run the queries against the simulator.

Patch Set 5:

> Patch Set 5:
> 
> > Patch Set 5:
> > 
> > @Jorge I checked the drools CSITs and they seem to be working fine with this change. Is there any other place I should check where drools is using the AAI simulator?
> 
> The aai simulator is used in the feature-controlloop-utils in drools-applications.   The s3p.jmx for jmeter in drools-applications is used for vfirewall, vcpe, .. and in the ONSETs carry the AAI info for the queries, it is typically used with the feature-controlloop-utils  The drools-applications junits for the usecases controller also run the queries against the simulator.

The only change in behavior to the existing AAI simulator is with GetPnfQuery. This needs correct pnf name to fetch the corresponding response file. Sample response which was already there can be fetched by using "demo-pnf" as the pnf name. Probably no changes will be needed anywhere similar to CSITs.

Patch Set 5: Code-Review+1

drools-applications is also verified and the junits seems to pass okay.
I don't think there will be any changes needed in jmx as well. Even if it is needed, it will be as simple as updating the pnf-name, as this is an improvement and provide more flexibility anyway.
So, I think we are good.

Patch Set 2:

As for the other patchset, I don't see the point to split tox lists in multiple runs.
For a very small gain in duration (not so sure), you would have quickly to manage excludes per branch.

Tox could be the only entry point and then you would only define default env lists per branches.
Here it asks for backports or to add exclude per stream.

Here is an example excluding streams:
https://git.opnfv.org/releng/tree/jjb/functest/xtesting.yaml#n217

Patch Set 2:

Sorry, just noticed Cedric's comment. Can you guys please respond to it?

Patch Set 3:

(1 comment)

> Patch Set 2:
> 
> As for the other patchset, I don't see the point to split tox lists in multiple runs.
> For a very small gain in duration (not so sure), you would have quickly to manage excludes per branch.
> 
> Tox could be the only entry point and then you would only define default env lists per branches.
> Here it asks for backports or to add exclude per stream.
> 
> Here is an example excluding streams:
> https://git.opnfv.org/releng/tree/jjb/functest/xtesting.yaml#n217

> Patch Set 2:
> 
> Sorry, just noticed Cedric's comment. Can you guys please respond to it?

Thanks Cédric for the example. I've tried to adapt here to the situation here.
Let me know if it is OK

@Jessica I'll let OOM committers answer about the other proposal because I don't know the reason behind the actual policy.
I agree with Cédric that managing directly env in OOM repo tox.ini files per branch would be much easier. The actual OOM policy is not to backport tox new linters to old branches as explained in
https://gerrit.onap.org/r/c/oom/+/120407
As the result, we have to configure every exclude combinatory, what can quickly become really cumbersome.
